  <h2>Streaming, VPN, and Digital Services</h2>
  <p>Gulf internet connections are generally fast and reliable for streaming services. Netflix, Amazon Prime Video, Disney+, and Apple TV+ all operate in the region with localized content libraries. Some content may be restricted or censored compared to Western libraries, and certain shows or movies may not be available. VPN usage is a grey area across the Gulf: using a VPN for privacy or business purposes is generally tolerated, but using one to access blocked content or services, commit fraud, or bypass government restrictions is illegal. In the UAE, unauthorized VPN use can carry fines of AED 500,000-2,000,000 (~€125,000-500,000), though enforcement typically targets commercial violations rather than personal browsing. Gaming services including PlayStation Network, Xbox Live, and Steam operate normally across all three countries. International news websites and social media platforms (Instagram, X/Twitter, Facebook, LinkedIn, TikTok) are accessible in all three countries, though some content may be filtered.</p>

  <h2>Practical Tips for Setting Up</h2>
  <p>To get connected quickly upon arriving in the Gulf, purchase a local prepaid SIM card at the airport immediately upon landing. All three countries require registration with your passport, and sometimes your visa or residency stamp. Airport kiosks for all major operators are typically open 24/7. Start with a prepaid data package sufficient for your first week, then switch to a postpaid plan once your residency is confirmed and your <a href="/guides/banking-expats-gulf/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">bank account</a> is open. For home internet, your landlord or building management can usually advise on which provider has pre-installed connections in the building, which avoids installation delays. This is worth confirming when arranging <a href="/uae/housing/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">your housing</a>. Installation for new connections typically takes 3-7 business days. Keep your home country mobile number active on a low-cost plan for two-factor authentication codes from banks and government services back home, and use eSIM to manage both lines on a single phone.</p>

